{"id":"1912.12036","submitter":"Andrei V. Lebedev","authors":"A. V. Lebedev, V. M. Vinokur","title":"Time-reversal of an unknown quantum state","comments":"5 pages","journal-ref":"Commun Phys 3, 129 (2020)","doi":"10.1038/s42005-020-00396-0","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For decades, researchers have sought to understand how the irreversibility of\nthe surrounding world emerges from the seemingly time symmetric, fundamental\nlaws of physics. Quantum mechanics conjectured a clue that final\nirreversibility is set by the measurement procedure and that the time reversal\nrequires complex conjugation of the wave function, which is overly complex to\nspontaneously appear in nature. Building on this Landau-Wigner conjecture, it\nbecame possible to demonstrate that time reversal is exponentially improbable\nin a virgin nature and to design an algorithm artificially reversing a time\narrow for a given quantum state on the IBM quantum computer. However, the\nimplemented arrow-of-time reversal embraced only the known states initially\ndisentangled from the thermodynamic reservoir. Here we develop a procedure for\nreversing the temporal evolution of an arbitrary unknown quantum state. This\nopens the route for general universal algorithms sending temporal evolution of\nan arbitrary system backwards in time.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Dec 2019 09:23:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-22"}
